English:
The trip to Asia has not meant that other parts of the world have become irrelevant. On the contrary, Europe’s economy has been much larger and richer than China’s. But, as Obama’s National Security Advisor Tom Donilon recently declared, US foreign policy in recent years has been buffeted heavily by the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, by threats from terrorism and the proliferation of nuclear weapons in Iran and North Korea, and by uprisings in the Arab world. Obama’s November trip to Asia was an effort to align US foreign policy priorities with the region’s long-term importance of the region.

