English:
There are some truly elite individuals for this job, individuals who have demonstrated their expertise in economic development as well as their intelligence, personal integrity, and organizational and political skills. These potential candidates include former Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, a Yale graduate who is now teaching at Yale and has been heavily endorsed in a Financial Times editorial. Moreover, Arminio Fraga, a Princeton graduate who was former governor of Brazil’s central bank, and Kemal Dervis, a former World Bank vice president who taught at Princeton and successfully led Turkey through its crisis as finance minister. Why should the world settle for less than a candidate of this calibre?

